04852nam a22005535i 9780822384502DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223845027 a10.1515/97808223845022doi  a(DE-B1597)552171  a(OCoLC)658114602  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBL65.W48bG37 2003 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aGardell, Mattias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGods of the Blood :bThe Pagan Revival and White Separatism /cMattias Gardell. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b26 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Globalization, Nationalism, and the Pagan Revival -- t1. The Transforming Landscapes of American Racism -- t2. The Smorgasbord of the Revolutionary White-Racist Counterculture -- t3. The Pagan Revival -- t4.Wolf-Age Pagans: The Odinist Call of Aryan Revolutionary Paganism -- t5. By the Spear of Odin: The Rise of Wotansvolk -- t6. Ethnic Asatrú -- t7. Hail Loki! Hail Satan! Hail Hitler! Darkside Asatrú, Satanism, and Occult National Socialism -- t8. Globalization, Aryan Paganism, and Romantic Men with Guns -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRacist paganism is a thriving but understudied element of the American religious and cultural landscape. Gods of the Blood is the first in-depth survey of the people, ideologies, and practices that make up this fragmented yet increasingly radical and militant milieu. Over a five-year period during the 1990s Mattias Gardell observed and participated in pagan ceremonies and interviewed pagan activists across the United States. His unprecedented entree into this previously obscure realm is the basis for this firsthand account of the proliferating web of organizations and belief systems combining pre-Christian pagan mythologies with Aryan separatism. Gardell outlines the historical development of the different strands of racist paganism-including Wotanism, Odinism and Darkside Asatrú-and situates them on the spectrum of pagan belief ranging from Wicca and goddess worship to Satanism.Gods of the Blood details the trends that have converged to fuel militant paganism in the United States: anti-government sentiments inflamed by such events as Ruby Ridge and Waco, the rise of the white power music industry (including whitenoise, dark ambient, and hatecore), the extraordinary reach of modern communications technologies, and feelings of economic and cultural marginalization in the face of globalization and increasing racial and ethnic diversity of the American population. Gardell elucidates how racist pagan beliefs are formed out of various combinations of conspiracy theories, anti-Semitism, warrior ideology, populism, beliefs in racial separatism, Klandom, skinhead culture, and tenets of national socialism. He shows how these convictions are further animated by an array of thought selectively derived from thinkers including Nietzche, historian Oswald Spengler, Carl Jung, and racist mystics. Scrupulously attentive to the complexities of racist paganism as it is lived and practiced, Gods of the Blood is a fascinating, disturbing, and important portrait of the virulent undercurrents of certain kinds of violence in America today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPaganismzUnited States. 0aPaganism. 0aWhite supremacy movementsxReligious aspects. 0aWhite supremacy movementszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082